Florus also, the Historian, speaks of Thessaly, and the plains of Phi- lippi, as the same place: ‘⁶ Sic prae- “ cipitantibus fatis, praelio sumta est “ Thessalia, et Philippicis campis, “ urbis, imperii, generis humani fata ‘⁶ commissa sunt.” Perhaps both Pliny and Servius are in the right, of whom the former, as has been al.. ready observed, says Macedon was anciently called Emathia, and the latter says the same of Thessaly: for it is not impossible that Macedon, Thessaly, and Epirus might have been anciently included under the name of Emathia.
